    <div class="container mt-5">
        <h1>About Systems Monitor</h1>
        <p>Systems Monitor is an open-source application designed to help users monitor
            the performance and health of their computer systems in real-time.</p>

        <h2>Features</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Real-time monitoring of CPU, memory, and disk usage</li>
            <li>Historical data logging and visualization</li>
            <li>User-friendly interface with detailed system information</li>
            <li>Lightweight and efficient, designed to run with minimal system impact</li>
            <li>Data range shows system metric average, minimum, max, and latest over the time period</li>
        </ul>

    </div>
    <div class="container mt-5">
        <h2>What do the metrics mean?</h2>
        <div class="container mt-5">
            <div class="card mb-3 shadow-sm">
                <div class="card-body">
                    <h3 class="h5">CPU Metrics</h3>
                    <table class="table table-striped">
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Metric</th>
                                <th>One sentence description</th>
                                <th>Summary</th>
                                <th>Units</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>CPU Total Percentage</td>
                                <td>How busy the CPU is overall</td>
                                <td>The percent of time the CPU is busy executing tasks
                                    (running programs, handling background tasks) instead of being idle.
                                    A higher CPU usage percentage indicates that the CPU is working harder.
                                </td>
                                <td>%</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>CPU User Percentage</td>
                                <td>Time spent by CPU running user processes</td>
                                <td>The percent of time the CPU is busy running user applications and programs.
                                    Higher user CPU usage indicates that applications are actively
                                    using the CPU for processing tasks.
                                </td>
                                <td>%</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>CPU System Percentage</td>
                                <td>Time spent by CPU running system (kernel) processes</td>
                                <td>The percent of time the CPU is busy running system-level tasks
                                    (operating system functions and background processes).
                                    Higher system CPU usage can indicate that there is heavy OS activity.
                                </td>
                                <td>%</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Load Averages (1, 5, 15 min)</td>
                                <td>Average system load over 1, 5, and 15 minutes</td>
                                <td>Represents the average number of processes that are either
                                    in a runnable or uninterruptible state over the specified time intervals.
                                    Higher load averages can indicate a heavily loaded system.
                                </td>
                                <td>Number of processes</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>CPU Per Core Percentage</td>
                                <td>How busy each CPU core is</td>
                                <td>The percentage of time each individual CPU core is busy executing tasks.
                                    This metric provides a more granular view of CPU usage across all cores.
                                </td>
                                <td>%</td>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="card mb-3 shadow-sm">
                <div class="card-body">
                    <h3 class="h5">Memory Metrics</h3>
                    <table class="table table-striped">
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Metric</th>
                                <th>One sentence description</th>
                                <th>Summary</th>
                                <th>Units</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Memory Used Percentage</td>
                                <td>The amount of RAM memory being used</td>
                                <td>The percent of total system memory (RAM) that is currently in use.
                                    Higher memory usage can indicate that applications are consuming more memory,
                                    which may lead to slower performance if the system runs low on available memory.
                                </td>
                                <td>%/GB</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Memory Free</td>
                                <td>The amount of RAM memory that is free</td>
                                <td>The amount of RAM memory that is currently not being used by any applications or
                                    processes.
                                    Sufficient free memory is important for system performance, as it allows
                                    the system to allocate memory to new applications and processes as needed.
                                </td>
                                <td>GB</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Memory Available</td>
                                <td>The amount of RAM memory that is available for use</td>
                                <td>The amount of RAM memory that is readily available for use by applications and
                                    processes.
                                    This includes both free memory and memory that can be quickly reclaimed from caches.
                                    Having sufficient available memory is crucial for maintaining optimal system
                                    performance.
                                </td>
                                <td>GB</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="card mb-3 shadow-sm">
                <div class="card-body">
